The data will be saved in the file The trip data has been stored correctly. Remember to change the terminal settings to force 2G-GSM to be used, otherwise erroneous data may be given. Something went wrong in getting the signal. CLOSE RSRP (Reference Signal Received Power), is a measure of the radio signal strength received by a mobile device from a specific cellular tower in a cellular network. RSRP is one of the key parameters used to assess the quality of the radio link between a mobile device and a cell tower in Long Term Evolution (LTE) and 5G networks.

A higher RSRP value indicates a stronger signal, which generally means better network coverage and potentially higher data transfer rates. On the other hand, a lower RSRP value indicates a weaker signal, which can result in poor network performance, dropped calls and slower data transfer speeds. It is expressed in dBm.

The following scale has been used to evaluate signal quality: RSSI (Received Signal Strength Indicator) is a parameter used in wireless networks to measure the signal strength received by a wireless receiver from a wireless transmitter. In other words, RSSI indicates the strength of the wireless signal reaching a receiving device.

In 2G mobile networks, RSSI expressed in dBm, always has a negative value. The maximum power (at the same tower) corresponds to -51 and the minimum with which a connection can be established (the furthest location) corresponds to -113.

